## 9. Why the inaccurate ARCHIVE_MARKER matters

The TZ-93 ARCHIVE_MARKER was written in good faith based on a browser-use failure observed during TZ-93 implementation (commit `753d6d6` 2026-07-11). At the time, the failure manifested as "page redirects to /login" — which was attributed to an auth wall. But the actual cause was likely:

1. The dev proxy wasn't running, so any page that referenced `/api/*` failed silently
2. The auth interceptor (which is global) was probing `/api/auth/me` on app init, getting a network error, and triggering the fallback redirect to `/login`
3. This made it LOOK like /kit/* was gated, when actually the auth interceptor was the culprit (and it's supposed to be global, not per-route)

**Lesson learned:** When debugging "page redirects to /login" in dev, check the auth interceptor logs FIRST, not the route config. The route config is deterministic; the interceptor has many failure modes (network errors, token expiry, etc.).

**This is a documentation issue, not a code issue.** The route config was correct all along; the ARCHIVE_MARKER misdiagnosed the failure mode. TZ-92b fixes the documentation and adds defensive tests so the misdiagnosis doesn't propagate further.

